
Step 1: Set up a new React project 
----------------------------------
Open your terminal or command prompt and run the following command to create a new React application using Vite: 

npm create vite@latest calculator-app -- --template react
cd calculator-app
npm install
npm run dev

This will create a new directory calculator-app, install necessary dependencies, and start the development server. You can view your application in a web browser, usually at http://localhost:5173. 

Step 2: Replace the content of App.jsx 
--------------------------------------
Open the calculator-app directory in your code editor and replace the entire content of the file src/App.jsx with the code below. This single component will handle all the calculator's functionality and styling. 

App.jsx
-------
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import './App.css'; // You will create this file next

const Calculator = () => {
  const [input, setInput] = useState('');
  const [result, setResult] = useState('');

  const handleClick = (value) => {
    if (value === '=') {
      try {
        // Using eval() is simple for this basic example, but in a real-world app,
        // you would use a safer expression evaluation library.
        setResult(eval(input).toString());
      } catch (error) {
        setResult('Error');
      }
    } else if (value === 'C') {
      setInput('');
      setResult('');
    } else {
      setInput(input + value);
    }
  };

  const buttons = [
    '7', '8', '9', '/',
    '4', '5', '6', '*',
    '1', '2', '3', '-',
    '0', '.', '=', '+',
    'C'
  ];

  return (
    <div className="calculator-container">
      <div className="display">
        <div className="input">{input}</div>
        <div className="result">{result}</div>
      </div>
      <div className="buttons">
        {buttons.map((button) => (
          <button
            key={button}
            onClick={() => handleClick(button)}
            className={`button ${button === '=' || button === 'C' ? 'operator' : ''}`}
          >
            {button}
          </button>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default Calculator;

Step 3: Add styling in App.css 
------------------------------
Next, replace the entire content of the file src/App.css with the CSS code below. This will style the calculator to look like a functional device. 

App.css
-------
.calculator-container {
  width: 300px;
  margin: 50px auto;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
  border-radius: 10px;
  padding: 10px;
  background-color: #f7f7f7;
  box-shadow: 0 4px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
}

.display {
  background-color: #eee;
  padding: 15px;
  text-align: right;
  border-radius: 5px;
  margin-bottom: 10px;
  min-height: 50px;
}

.input {
  font-size: 1.2rem;
  color: #555;
  min-height: 1.2rem;
}

.result {
  font-size: 1.8rem;
  font-weight: bold;
  color: #333;
}

.buttons {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
  gap: 10px;
}

.button {
  padding: 15px;
  font-size: 1.2rem;
  border: none;
  border-radius: 5px;
  cursor: pointer;
  background-color: #fff;
  transition: background-color 0.2s;
}

.button:hover {
  background-color: #e9e9e9;
}

.operator {
  background-color: #ff9800;
  color: white;
}

.operator:hover {
  background-color: #e68900;
}

Step 4: Run the application
---------------------------
Your development server should still be running. If not, start it again from your terminal: 

                      npm run dev
